{"id":"1508.01373","submitter":"Mairi Walker","authors":"Ian Short and Mairi Walker","title":"Even-integer continued fractions and the Farey tree","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Singerman introduced to the theory of maps on surfaces an object that is a\nuniversal cover for any map. This object is a tessellation of the hyperbolic\nplane together with a certain subset of the ideal boundary. The 1-skeleton of\nthis tessellation comprises the edges of an infinite tree whose vertices belong\nto the ideal boundary. Here we show how this tree can be used to give a\nbeautiful geometric representation of even-integer continued fractions. We use\nthis representation to prove some of the fundamental theorems on even-integer\ncontinued fractions that are already known, and we also prove some new theorems\nwith this technique, which have familiar counterparts in the theory of regular\ncontinued fractions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 Aug 2015 12:22:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-08-07"}
