{"id":"1508.01808","submitter":"Jerrold Franklin","authors":"Jerrold Franklin","title":"What is the force on a magnetic dipole?","comments":"This version presents a more compelling argument that the textbook\n  equation for the force on a magnetic dipole is correct, and is needed to\n  preserve overall momentum conservation","journal-ref":"2018 Eur. J. Phys. 39 035201","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.class-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We show that attempts to modify the force on a magnetic dipole by introducing\neither hidden momentum or internal forces are not correct. The standard\ntextbook result ${\\bf F=\\nabla(\\bmu\\cdot B)}$ is correct even in the presence\nof time dependent electromagnetic fields. Using this expression for the force,\noverall momentum (the sum of mechanical and electromagnetic momentum) is\nconserved in changing electromagnetic fields.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 6 Aug 2015 15:03:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 8 Sep 2015 17:43:53 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 10 Jan 2016 14:45:45 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 20 Sep 2017 18:32:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-04-11"}
